        routeDescription: "The route takes the N12, a toll-free dual carriageway crossing northern Brittany via Morlaix, Guingamp and Saint-Brieuc.",
        introduction: "Saint-Brieuc is the prefecture of Cotes-d'Armor, a dynamic city perched on a plateau overlooking a vast bay. The Bay of Saint-Brieuc, a National Nature Reserve, is one of Brittany's largest bays with 800 hectares of foreshore exposed at low tide — a paradise for migratory birds, with over 40,000 waders stopping each year on the Arctic route. The city preserves a rich medieval heritage including Saint-Etienne Cathedral, a fortified Gothic structure from the 13th-14th centuries with two massive towers giving it a unique martial appearance. Saint-Brieuc is also France's scallop capital, hosting the annual Fete de la Coquille Saint-Jacques in April. Taxis from Brest serve business travellers, families heading to the north coast, and tourists transiting between Finistere and Cotes-d'Armor.",
        itineraire: "Your driver takes the N12 towards Rennes, the main artery crossing all of northern Brittany. The expressway is entirely toll-free and dual carriageway for most of the journey. Leaving Brest via the Iroise bridge, you cross the Leon plateau with its vegetable fields and parish closes. After Landivisiau, you pass beneath the Morlaix viaduct without entering the town. The road continues through the Tregor region of granite and legend, through Guingamp and its basilica. After Guingamp, you follow the Trieux valley then climb to the Saint-Brieuc plateau. Arrival is via the southern bypass with clear views over the bay in fine weather. The journey takes 1h30 normally and up to 1h55 during summer peak periods or Friday evenings.",
